                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="notes">
                    
                        <note n="1" xml:id="note-t-1">
                            

<p>This tower could be seen from the parsonage garden. Altogether fifteen works showing the tower with the churchyard around it are known; they were done between December 1883 and May 1885. See exhib. cat. ’s-Hertogenbosch 1987 and De Brouwer 2000. This is probably <hi rend="italics">The old church tower at Nuenen with a ploughman</hi> (<rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2453">F 34 / JH 459</rs>), cf. <ref target="let440.xml#n-9">letter 440, n. 9.</ref></p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="2" xml:id="note-t-2">
                            

<p>We cannot say for certain exactly which pen-and-ink drawings he is referring to here; cf. <ref target="let430.xml#n-1">letter 430, n. 1.</ref></p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="3" xml:id="note-t-3">
                            

<p><rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1262">Aloysius O’Kelly</rs>, <hi rend="italics">Departure of Irish emigrants at Clifden, County Galway</hi>, engraved by <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1582">William James Palmer</rs>, in <hi rend="italics">The Illustrated London News</hi> 83 (21 July 1883), pp. 68-69. <rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_1208">Ill. 1208</rs>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="4" xml:id="note-t-4">
                            

<p><rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_999">Alfred Edward Emslie</rs>, <hi rend="italics">At work in a woollen factory</hi>, engraved by <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1537">Eugène Froment</rs>, in <hi rend="italics">The Illustrated London News</hi> 83 (25 August 1883), p. 181. Van Gogh’s copy is in the estate. <rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_812">Ill. 812</rs> (t*150).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="5" xml:id="note-t-5">
                            

<p><rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1297">Charles Stanley Reinhart,</rs> <hi rend="italics">For those in peril upon the sea</hi>, engraved by <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1591">Charles Roberts</rs>, in the Christmas issue of <hi rend="italics">The Graphic</hi> 1883, p. 30. <rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_1255">Ill. 1255</rs>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="6" xml:id="note-t-6">
                            

<p>Van Gogh had been familiar with <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_899">Jules Breton</rs>’s poetry for some time. He had read the collection <hi rend="italics"><ref target="biblio.xml#lit_29">Les champs et la mer</ref> </hi>(1875), which he had sent Theo in December 1875 (<ref target="let034.xml">see letters 34</ref> and <ref target="let061.xml">61</ref>). Not long after this he copied out more poems from it for <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1306">Van Rappard</rs>. <ref target="let435.xml">See letter 435</ref>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="7" xml:id="note-t-7">
                            

<p>
      <hi rend="italics"><ref target="biblio.xml#lit_371">Les humbles</ref> </hi>and <hi rend="italics"><ref target="biblio.xml#lit_383">Promenades et intérieurs</ref></hi> (<hi rend="italics">Humble folk </hi>and <hi rend="italics">Walks and interiors</hi>) are chapter headings in <hi rend="italics"><ref target="biblio.xml#lit_368">Poesies de François Coppée</ref></hi> (Coppée 1880).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="8" xml:id="note-t-8">
                            

<p><rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1306">Van Rappard</rs> worked on his painting <hi rend="italics">Sounding the vespers</hi> (present whereabouts unknown) in the winter of 1883-1884. <rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2120">Ill. 2120</rs>. The work was exhibited at the National Exhibition (Nationale Tentoonstelling) in Utrecht (cat. no. 103) in March 1884. See exhib. cat. Amsterdam 1974, p. 86, cat. no. 108.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="9" xml:id="note-t-9">
                            

<p>Van Gogh jotted this postscript on the back of the envelope.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                            

                        
                    
